--clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/TU_USUARIO/iiot-fault-detection.git
cd iiot-fault-detection

--Create and activate a virtual environment (required to interact with the app)
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate   # Linux/Mac
venv\Scripts\activate      # Windows

--install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

--Configure the database
Make sure you have PostgreSQL running and create a database (for example, iiot_lab). Then run the SQL scripts in order to create the necessary tables and views:

psql -U postgres -d iiot_lab -f sql/schema.sql
psql -U postgres -d iiot_lab -f sql/views_for_training_v4.sql
psql -U postgres -d iiot_lab -f sql/vibration_wide_full.sql
psql -U postgres -d iiot_lab -f sql/session_pairs_byfile.sql
psql -U postgres -d iiot_lab -f sql/aligned_ct_vib_views_v3.sql

Note: Adjust the username (postgres) and password according to your configuration. You can use environment variables or modify the commands.

--Data Ingestion- Place the dataset files in a folder (for example, ./data) and run:
python ingesttodatabase.py \
  --data_dir ./data \
  --dsn "postgresql://postgres:tu_contrase√±a@localhost:5432/iiot_lab" \
  --asset MOTOR_001 \
  --overwrite

Model Training
To train the models (IsolationForest, SGD Logistic and the merged CT+VIB) for loads of 0, 2 and 4 Nm:

--Run the API --The API allows you to make real-time predictions using the trained models.
cd api
uvicorn api_app:app --reload --port 8000

-Run the Dashboard- Dashboards allow you to view the model's training data
streamlit run dashboard/dashboard.py


